:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of various places in northern France called Vaux, from the Old French plural of <i>val</i> ‘valley’. Compare English   Vause   and French   Devaux  .","History: Richard Vaux (1749–90) emigrated from Sussex, England, to Philadelphia, PA, in early youth. Calvert Vaux, landscape architect, emigrated from London, England, to America in 1850 and designed several major US parks, including Central Park in New York City (with Frederick Olmstead). — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its variant <i>Veaux</i> and altered form   Devoe  ) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Vause","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire):","of Norman origin, a habitational name from Vaux (see   Vaux  ), a common French placename, singular and plural of <i>val</i> ‘valley’, the plural form being Latinized in surnames as <i>de Vallibus</i>. Norman lords with this surname are recorded in 12th- and early 13th-century records in Cumberland (Irthington), Devon (Farwood, in Colyton), East Yorkshire (Warter), Essex (Belchamp), and Leicestershire (Belvoir). Compare   Vale  .","nickname perhaps from Middle English <i>fals</i>, <i>faus</i>, <i>vaus</i> (Old French <i>fals</i>, <i>faus</i>, Old English <i>fals</i>) ‘deceitful, disloyal, dishonest, mendacious’, but it is more likely the name arises from 1, with the common Anglo-Norman French substitution of <i>le</i> for <i>de</i> in their surname."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":16,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":26,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":36,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Vaux was born in 1070, in Vaux-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Normandy, France. He married Beatrice de Munchensy in 1101, in Vaux, Moselle, Grand Est, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in England, and was buried in Pentney, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"about 1070–":"1070–Surnud","1085–1109":"1085–1109","1102–1167":"1102–1167","1104–1153":"1104–1153","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","about 1070":"1070","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1137":"1137","1102":"1102","1101":"1101","1167":"1167","1827":"1827","1109":"1109","Pentney, Norfolk, England":"Pentney, Norfolk, England","Vaux-sur-Seulles, Duché de Normandie":"Vaux-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","England":"England","Irthington, Cumberland, England":"Irthington, Cumberland, England","Vaux-sur-Seules, Duché de Normadie":"Vaux, Moselle, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Vaux-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Duche de Normandy, France":"Vaux-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1070–":"1070–Kuollut","1085–1109":"1085–1109","1102–1167":"1102–1167","1104–1153":"1104–1153","1070–Male":"1070–Kuollut","about 1070":"1070","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1137":"1137","1102":"1102","1101":"1101","1167":"1167","1827":"1827","1109":"1109","Pentney, Norfolk, England":"Pentney, Norfolk, England","Vaux-sur-Seulles, Duché de Normandie":"Vaux-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Normandie, Ranska","England":"England","Irthingt